<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-582-292 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 582 292.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Los Angeles Times  April 10 1991 v110 pD3 11 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. risks high-tech talent gap.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Saffo, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There is growing concern among the high technology industriesabout the steady decline in the number of US citizens choosingcareers in science and technology.andP;  The void that has threatenedto engulf the high-tech industries in the past decade has beenfilled by foreign students.andP;  This trend is even more apparent inthe light of the fact that the percentage of computer sciencegraduate degrees awarded to foreign students in the US has risenfrom 32 percent in 1977 to 45 percent a decade later.andP;  Theabundance of foreign engineers in the US has led to companies suchas Sony, Fujitsu, and Canon establishing research and developmentcenters in California.andP;  Many foreign companies are also attemptingto recruit professionals outside of the US, using the lure of moremoney and exotic locations to attract workers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryHigh technologyEmployment OpportunityUnited StatesBrain drainOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>